gress a means to repair flawed statutes, reconcile discordant court decisions, and reverse errant judicial interpretations. Overrides also allow dissatisfied litigants to revisit issues and raise concerns in Congress that courts have overlooked. Of course, promising is one thing and delivering is quite another. Accordingly, this book asks: Do overrides, in fact, effectively clarify the law, reverse objectionable judicial statutory interpretations, and broaden deliberation on contested issues? The answers provide new insights into the complex role of overrides in U.S. policy-making and in the politics of contemporary court-Congress relations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aContrôle juridictionnel des loisxÉtats-Unis. 0aDroitxInterprétationxÉtats-Unis. 0aJudicial reviewxUnited States. 0aJudicial reviewzUnited States. 0aLawxInterpretation and constructionxUnited States. 0aLawzUnited StatesxInterpretation and construction. 0aPolitical questions and judicial powerxUnited States. 0aPolitical questions and judicial powerzUnited States. 0aPolitique et pouvoir judiciairexÉtats-UnisxUnited States. 0aStatutesxUnited States. 0aStatuteszUnited States. 0aStatutsxÉtats-Unis. 4aLaw -- Constitutional Law and U.S. Courts. 4aPolitics -- United States. 7aLAW / Legal History.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080476720040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804767200423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780804767200/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles